'''Mathías Olivera Miramontes''' (born 31 October 1997) is a Uruguayan professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] or [[centre-back]] for {{Italian football updater|Napoli}} club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] and the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay national team]].

After starting his career with few appearance at his home country, he moved to Spanish club Getafe, where he spent five seasons while also being loaned to Albacete in 2018–19. After five years in Spain, he joined Italian club Napoli, winning the Serie A titles in 2022–23 and 2024–25.

Olivera is a former youth international for Uruguay, he made his debut at senior level in January 2022, representing the country at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2024 Copa América]].

==Club career==
===Uruguay===
Born in [[Montevideo]], Olivera is a [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]] youth graduate. After progressing through the youth setup, he made his professional debut on 13 February 2016, starting and being [[Penalty card#Yellow card|booked]] in a 3–0 away win against [[Club Atlético River Plate (Montevideo)|River Plate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenfield.com.uy/river-00-nacional/|title=Nacional letal y contundente; 3:0|trans-title=Lethal and overwhelming Nacional, 3–0|publisher=[[Tenfield]]|language=es|date=13 February 2016|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>

Olivera appeared in only one further match for the club, a 2–0 loss at [[Club Plaza Colonia de Deportes|Plaza Colonia]] on 29 February 2016. In December of that year, he was bought outright by his agent [[Daniel Fonseca]] and assigned to [[Atenas de San Carlos]] in [[Uruguayan Segunda División|Segunda División]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.referi.uy/fonseca-se-lleva-al-juvenil-olivera-n1013120|title=Fonseca se lleva al juvenil Olivera|trans-title=Fonseca takes the youth player Olivera|publisher=Referi|language=es|date=24 December 2016|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>

In July 2017, Oliveira passed a medical examination at [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], but eventually did not sign a contract and subsequently returned to Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.referi.uy/la-sombra-fonseca-el-misterioso-pase-mathias-olivera-n1101221|title=La sombra de Fonseca en el misterioso pase de Mathías Olivera|trans-title=The shadow of Fonseca in the mysterious rights of Mathías Olivera|publisher=Referi|language=es|date=24 July 2017|accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>

===Getafe===
On 14 August 2017, Olivera signed a six-year deal with [[La Liga]] club [[Getafe CF|Getafe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getafecf.com/Noticia/tabid/137/Article/4617/Mathias-Oivera-nuevo-refuerzo-azulon.aspx|title=Mathías Oivera, nuevo refuerzo azulón|trans-title=Mathías Olivera, new ''azulón'' addition|publisher=Getafe CF|language=es|date=14 August 2017|accessdate=14 August 2017|archive-date=9 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210809213634/http://www.getafecf.com/Noticia/tabid/137/Article/4617/Mathias-Oivera-nuevo-refuerzo-azulon.aspx|url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on 21 April 2018, netting the game's only in a 1–0 win against [[SD Eibar|Eibar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Eibar vs. Getafe – 21 April 2018|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/04/21/spain/primera-division/sociedad-deportiva-eibar/getafe-club-de-futbol/2529573/|access-date=13 June 2020}}</ref>

====Loan to Albacete====
On 4 July 2018, [[Segunda División]] side [[Albacete Balompié|Albacete]] announced the signing of Olivera on a season-long loan deal. He played 15 matches and scored a goal for the club before his loan was cut short by Getafe on 25 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gracias, Mathías|url=https://www.albacetebalompie.es/noticia/gracias-mathias|access-date=13 June 2020}}</ref>

===Napoli===
On 26 May 2022, Italian [[Serie A]] club [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] announced the signing of Olivera on a three-year deal.<ref name="napoli">{{cite web|publisher=S.S.C. Napoli|title=Il Napoli ufficializza l'acquisto di Mathias Olivera|url=https://www.sscnapoli.it/static/news/Il-Napoli-ufficializza-l-acquisto-di-Mathias-Olivera-25182.aspx|date=26 May 2022|access-date=27 May 2022}}</ref>

==International career==
Olivera has represented Uruguay at youth level. He was part of [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|Uruguay under-20 team]] which won the [[2017 South American U-20 Championship]] and finished fourth at the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite tweet|number=856899785424596994|user=Uruguay|title=#Sub20 | Plantel de @Uruguay para el...|date=25 April 2017}}</ref>

On 7 January 2022, Olivera was named in Uruguay's 50-man preliminary squad for [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] matches against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] and [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auf.org.uy/reservados-vs-paraguay-venezuela/|title=Reservados vs. Paraguay y Venezuela|publisher=Uruguayan Football Association|date=7 January 2022|access-date=18 January 2022}}</ref> He made his senior team debut on 27 January 2022 in a 1–0 win over Paraguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getafecf.com/Noticia/tabid/137/Article/8032/Damian-Suarez-y-Olivera-debutan-con-Uruguay-con-victoria.aspx|title=Damián Suárez y Olivera debutan con Uruguay con victoria|publisher=Getafe CF|date=28 January 2022|access-date=29 January 2022}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Uruguay in a 2–2 [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] draw against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] on 12 October 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/684592/uruguay-colombia|title=Colombia 2–2 Uruguay (Oct 12, 2023)|publisher=ESPN|date=12 October 2023|access-date=2 July 2024}}</ref>

In June 2024, Olivera was called up to represent Uruguay at the [[2024 Copa América]]. In their final group stage match against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], he scored the only goal of a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/live/usmnt-loses-to-uruguay-crashes-out-of-copa-america-230001552.html|title=USMNT loses to Uruguay, crashes out of Copa América|publisher=Yahoo Sports|date=1 July 2024|access-date=2 July 2024}}</ref>

On 31 May 2026, Olivera was named in Uruguay's 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mundial 2026: Uruguay dio a conocer la lista de 26 convocados por Marcelo Bielsa|url=https://www.montevideo.com.uy/Deportes/Mundial-2026-Uruguay-dio-a-conocer-la-lista-de-26-convocados-por-Marcelo-Bielsa-uc963756|language=es|date=31 May 2026|access-date=31 May 2026}}</ref>

